===Verb===
{{en-verb|makes a scene|making a scene|made a scene}}

# {{lb|en|idiom}} To bring unnecessary [[attention]] to oneself, especially through a public expression of tumultuous emotion.
#* '''1814''', {{w|Elizabeth Cavendish, Duchess of Devonshire|Elizabeth Hervey}}, ''Amabel; or, Memoirs of a Woman of Fashion'', London: H. Colburn, Volume II, Part VIII, p. 287,<sup>[https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/006110081]</sup>
#*: I saw, though he tried to conceal it, that he was very much hurt at your behaviour, and I was sure, by his looks, that he did not think my jealous apprehension groundless; however, he protested he did, and persuaded me not to '''make a scene''' by arriving her in the middle of the night {{...}}
#* '''1893''', {{w|Henry James}}, “The Real Thing” in ''The Real Thing and Other Tales'', New York: Macmillan, p. 25,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/realthingotherta00jamerich]</sup>
#*: The next time I saw Miss Churm after this incident she surprised me greatly by '''making a scene''' about it—she accused me of having wished to humiliate her.
#* '''1935''', {{w|Christopher Isherwood}}, ''Mr Norris Changes Trains'', Penguin, 1942, Chapter Three, p. 32,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/mrnorrischangest00ishe]</sup>
#*: She snuggled against me, while from the other side a boy was amateurishly trying to pick my pocket. I opened my mouth to protest, but thought better of it. Why '''make a scene''' at the end of such an enjoyable evening?
#* '''2003''', Michael Berry (translator), ''{{w|To Live (novel)|To Live}}'' (1993) by {{w|Yu Hua}}, New York: Knopf Doubleday, 2007, p. 125,<sup>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=r5kKobqjHgwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false]</sup>
#*: This time I had really hurt my son. Youqing wasn’t upset because I had hit him, but because I had '''made a scene''' in front of so many of his teachers and classmates.

